Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members to the board of the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future course.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to miss its most important mandate—ensuring price stability so badly.
That the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional self-examination is certainly called for.
Yet while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
A further major question is therefore whether it will use its immense power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, deny credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant credit only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit towards desired alternatives.
In addition, it could decide to explicitly frame its regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by requiring banks to specify where and to whom loans are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the serious failure of the Fed.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a consequential decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments through the sale of short-term, interest-rate-sensitive debt instruments, but swarms of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the riskiness of the assets of these institutions.
The hope was that the regulatory agencies would no longer overlook such large chunks of subprime mortgages in the banks' balance sheets.
Yet in the subsequent ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army has not once questioned what actually happens in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually hit in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "Never again" promises from 2008 and intervened to an even greater extent.
In March, commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries on the market for ordinary U.S. government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The market corrections would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been put off for a long time.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but such runs never occurred.
In addition, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In the year 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package—the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in the year 2020, the "Powell put" — among other things — introduced an explicit floor for corporate bond prices.
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to COVID-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out every new fire with another flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
Why go through the trouble of using cash reserves or balance sheet capacity to buy at falling prices, provide liquidity, or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will anyway outperform them and pocket the profits.
Why issue shares as a company when one can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when buying dubious securities, if their value is guaranteed by another "whatever it takes" promise from the Fed during bad times?
No wonder that America is sinking into debt.
All assume that taxpayers will bear the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, government bonds, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operations.
Yet each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to pour more money into rescue operations, and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages everyone expects do not materialize, we will wake up in a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral hazard and were concerned that investors would reap profits in good times while taxpayers would bear the losses in bad times.
In 2020, the authorities indulged only in self-congratulation due to the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages in 2008 just as it failed to foresee the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about the mentioned events.
And although jargon about "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk at all, apart from it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulators overarching power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to foresee risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands behind mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit only a few Americans.
However, it starts from the wrong cause.
A massive effort to comply with regulations presents a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is futile.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unintended consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires regulatory authorities to have no prophetic abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the narrow banking and payment services sectors that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to the salvation of the planet and the redress of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it has fulfilled its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
